## What happened

**macOS has no native DSA support.** .NET's `DSA.Create()` returns a platform-native implementation, but Apple's Security framework dropped DSA. In .NET 11, this now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.

DSA itself has been obsolete (marked `[Obsolete]` with diagnostic `SYSLIB0047`) for several releases — .NET 11 tightened enforcement on platforms where no native provider exists.

## How to fix it

You have two options, depending on your constraints:

### Option 1: Use OpenSSL explicitly (if you must keep DSA)

```csharp
// Instead of DSA.Create(), use the OpenSSL-backed implementation directly.
// Requires OpenSSL installed on the Mac (e.g., via Homebrew).
using System.Security.Cryptography;

#pragma warning disable SYSLIB0047 // DSA is obsolete

if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = new DSAOpenSsl();      // OpenSSL-backed, works on macOS
    dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
    bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
}
else
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();          // native provider on Windows/Linux
    dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
    bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
}

#pragma warning restore SYSLIB0047
```

Make sure OpenSSL is available on the macOS build/run host:
```bash
brew install openssl
```

### Option 2: Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended)

DSA is cryptographically weak by today's standards. If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** — both are supported on all three platforms without caveats:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
```

### TL;DR

| | Windows | Linux | macOS |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DSA.Create()` | ✅ CNG | ✅ OpenSSL | ❌ `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `new DSAOpenSsl()` | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ (needs brew OpenSSL) |
| `ECDsa.Create()` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

If you're only **verifying** legacy signatures (read-only), `DSAOpenSsl` is the quickest path. For anything new, move to ECDSA/Ed25519.
